Phase 1: Install ArgoCD
Step 1 — Create ArgoCD namespace:

kubectl create namespace argocd

Step 2 — Install ArgoCD:

kubectl apply -n argocd -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/argoproj/argo-cd/stable/manifests/install.yaml


Step 3 — Wait for pods to be ready:

kubectl get pods -n argocd -w

# Expected output (all must be Running):
NAME                                   READY   STATUS
argocd-application-controller-0        1/1     Running
argocd-applicationset-controller-xxx   1/1     Running
argocd-dex-server-xxx                  1/1     Running
argocd-notifications-controller-xxx    1/1     Running
argocd-redis-xxx                       1/1     Running
argocd-repo-server-xxx                 1/1     Running
argocd-server-xxx                      1/1     Running

Phase 2: Access ArgoCD UI
You have 3 options to access:
Option 1 — Port forward (easiest for testing):            ----------  we did this

kubectl port-forward svc/argocd-server -n argocd 8080:443

# Now open browser:
https://localhost:8080

Option 2 — LoadBalancer (expose via AWS):

kubectl patch svc argocd-server \
  -n argocd \
  -p '{"spec": {"type": "LoadBalancer"}}'

# Get the external URL:
kubectl get svc argocd-server -n argocd

# Look for EXTERNAL-IP column
# Open browser: https://<EXTERNAL-IP>

Option 3 — Ingress (production way):

# We will cover this in Phase 6

Get initial admin password:

kubectl -n argocd get secret argocd-initial-admin-secret \
  -o jsonpath="{.data.password}" | base64 -d

# Login:
Username: admin
Password: <output from above command>


Phase 3: Setup Git Repo
Create this folder structure in your GitHub repo:

my-argocd-apps/
  └── sample-app/
       ├── deployment.yaml
       ├── service.yaml
       └── namespace.yaml

namespace.yaml:

apiVersion: v1
kind: Namespace
metadata:
  name: sample-app

deployment.yaml:

apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: sample-app
  namespace: sample-app
spec:
  replicas: 2
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: sample-app
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: sample-app
    spec:
      containers:
        - name: sample-app
          image: nginx:1.21        # simple nginx as sample app
          ports:
            - containerPort: 80
          resources:
            requests:
              cpu: "100m"
              memory: "128Mi"
            limits:
              cpu: "200m"
              memory: "256Mi"

service.yaml:

apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: sample-app-svc
  namespace: sample-app
spec:
  type: ClusterIP             # internal only
  selector:
    app: sample-app
  ports:
    - port: 80
      targetPort: 80

Phase 4: Deploy Sample App via ArgoCD          --- we can create in ArgoCD UI or in local and apply 
Create ArgoCD Application:

# application.yaml
apiVersion: argoproj.io/v1alpha1
kind: Application
metadata:
  name: sample-app
  namespace: argocd
spec:
  project: default

  source:
    repoURL: https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/my-argocd-apps
    targetRevision: main
    path: sample-app              # folder in your repo

  destination:
    server: https://kubernetes.default.svc
    namespace: sample-app

  syncPolicy:
    automated:
      prune: true                 # delete resources removed from git
      selfHeal: true              # revert manual changes ✅
    syncOptions:
      - CreateNamespace=true      # auto create namespace

Apply it:

kubectl apply -f application.yaml

Check status:

kubectl get application -n argocd

# Expected:
NAME         SYNC STATUS   HEALTH STATUS
sample-app   Synced        Healthy       ✅

Phase 5: See GitOps in Action
This is the most important part — watch ArgoCD work:
Test 1 — Change something in Git:

# In deployment.yaml change replicas from 2 to 4
spec:
  replicas: 4    # changed from 2

git add . && git commit -m "scale to 4 replicas" && git push

# ArgoCD detects change within 3 minutes
# automatically applies it to cluster

kubectl get pods -n sample-app
# You will see 4 pods running ✅

Test 3 — Manual change gets reverted:

# Manually scale to 10 replicas
kubectl scale deployment sample-app \
  --replicas=10 -n sample-app

# ArgoCD sees manual change
# Reverts back to 4 (what Git says) ✅
# selfHeal: true does this automatically

Phase 6: ArgoCD with Helm
More advanced — deploy using Helm chart:

# helm-application.yaml
apiVersion: argoproj.io/v1alpha1
kind: Application
metadata:
  name: nginx-helm
  namespace: argocd
spec:
  project: default

  source:
    repoURL: https://charts.bitnami.com/bitnami
    chart: nginx
    targetRevision: 15.0.0        # helm chart version

    helm:
      values: |
        replicaCount: 2
        service:
          type: ClusterIP

  destination:
    server: https://kubernetes.default.svc
    namespace: nginx-helm

  syncPolicy:
    automated:
      prune: true
      selfHeal: true
    syncOptions:
      - CreateNamespace=true

kubectl apply -f helm-application.yaml

# Check in UI or:
kubectl get application -n argocd

Phase 7: App of Apps Pattern
Managing multiple apps — the production way:

my-argocd-apps/
  ├── apps/                     ← App of Apps (parent)
  │    └── applications.yaml
  ├── sample-app/               ← child app 1
  │    ├── deployment.yaml
  │    └── service.yaml
  ├── monitoring/               ← child app 2
  │    ├── prometheus.yaml
  │    └── grafana.yaml
  └── ingress/                  ← child app 3
       └── nginx-ingress.yaml

Parent application watches all child apps:

# apps/applications.yaml
apiVersion: argoproj.io/v1alpha1
kind: Application
metadata:
  name: parent-app
  namespace: argocd
spec:
  project: default
  source:
    repoURL: https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/my-argocd-apps
    targetRevision: main
    path: apps                   # watches the apps folder
  destination:
    server: https://kubernetes.default.svc
    namespace: argocd
  syncPolicy:
    automated:
      prune: true
      selfHeal: true

Result:
  Push one YAML to Git
  ArgoCD deploys ALL apps automatically ✅
  Add new app? just add folder to Git ✅
  Remove app? just delete folder from Git ✅

